    <section class="section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-container">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              Should I choose the A7 IV or A7C II?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>Choose the A7 IV if you need the professional grip, dual card slots, and better button layout for fast-paced work. The A7C II is better if portability is paramount and you're primarily shooting travel or everyday content. Both share the same sensor and AF system, so image quality is identical.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              Is the Sony A7 IV good for sports photography?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>It's capable for casual sports with 10fps shooting and excellent Eye AF, but it's not ideal for professional sports. The buffer clears slower than dedicated sports cameras, and the mechanical shutter can cause blackout. For serious sports work, consider the A9 III or A1 which offer 30fps+ with no blackout.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              Does the A7 IV overheat during video recording?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>With the latest firmware, overheating is well-managed. You can shoot 4K60 for 45-60 minutes continuously in most conditions. The S35 crop mode runs cooler than full-frame. In hot weather (30¬∞C+), enable "High" temperature mode in settings to extend recording time.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              What memory cards should I use with the A7 IV?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>For 4K60 10-bit, use UHS-II V60 cards minimum (like Sony SF-G or ProGrade Digital). For 4K30, V30 cards work fine. The CFexpress Type A slot is overkill unless you shoot 4K120 or need faster buffer clearing for bursts. Save money and stick with UHS-II cards.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              Can the A7 IV use older E-mount lenses?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>Yes, all Sony E-mount lenses work perfectly, including older FE and even APS-C lenses (which auto-crop). Third-party lenses from Sigma, Tamron, and Samyang also work well, though some older models may need firmware updates for full compatibility with the advanced AF system.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

